04168nam a22006975i 9780813562513DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012051444  a97808135625137 a10.36019/97808135625132doi  a(DE-B1597)526497  a(OCoLC)863038960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPS153.N5bL68 2013 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.98960732231 aLordi, Emily J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Resonance :bIconic Women Singers and African American Literature /cEmily J. Lordi. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b11 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Literatures Initiative0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEver since Bessie Smith’s powerful voice conspired with the “race records” industry to make her a star in the 1920s, African American writers have memorialized the sounds and theorized the politics of black women’s singing. In Black Resonance, Emily J. Lordi analyzes writings by Richard Wright, Ralph Ellison, James Baldwin, Gayl Jones, and Nikki Giovanni that engage such iconic singers as Bessie Smith, Billie Holiday, Mahalia Jackson, and Aretha Franklin. Focusing on two generations of artists from the 1920s to the 1970s, Black Resonance reveals a musical-literary tradition in which singers and writers, faced with similar challenges and harboring similar aims, developed comparable expressive techniques. Drawing together such seemingly disparate works as Bessie Smith’s blues and Richard Wright’s neglected film of Native Son, Mahalia Jackson’s gospel music and Ralph Ellison’s Invisible Man, each chapter pairs one writer with one singer to crystallize the artistic practice they share: lyricism, sincerity, understatement, haunting, and the creation of a signature voice. In the process, Lordi demonstrates that popular female singers are not passive muses with raw, natural, or ineffable talent. Rather, they are experimental artists who innovate black expressive possibilities right alongside their literary peers. The first study of black music and literature to centralize the music of black women, Black Resonance offers new ways of reading and hearing some of the twentieth century’s most beloved and challenging voices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican American women in literature. 0aAfrican American women singersxIn literature. 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356251340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813562513/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK